CongestionDegradation
=====================

Overview
- This scenario generates pre-failure telemetry through traffic-driven congestion on the primary r2-r3 path.
- It keeps the same dual-path topology and OSPF structure as the other dissertation scenarios.
- Unlike the synthetic linkdegradation scenario, it does not inject delay or packet error rate directly into the channel.
- It should be treated as a controlled traffic-driven congestion approximation, not as a calibrated carrier-grade failure model.
- It currently provides two traffic-load profiles in the same scenario:
  - `CongestionDegradation` for the stronger congestion case
  - `CongestionDegradationMild` for a milder congestion case

Topology
- Primary path: hostA -> r1 -> r2 -> r3 -> hostB
- Backup path: hostA -> r1 -> r4 -> r3 -> hostB
- The primary r2-r3 link is a fixed 10 Mbps bottleneck.
- All other links remain at 100 Mbps.

Timeline
- 0s-20s: routing convergence, no traffic
- 20s-50s: baseline and light load with only the probe flow and the first bulk flow
- 50s-125s: staged demand rise as additional bulk flows start
- 125s-150s: critical congestion period with all configured flows active
- 150s: physical disconnect of r2-r3 by ScenarioManager
- 150s-180s: post-failure observation

Traffic
- Probe flow: 256 B every 10 ms, starts at 20 s
- Strong case bulk flows: 1200 B every 2 ms
- Strong case bulk flow start times: 30 s, 50 s, 65 s, 80 s, 95 s, 110 s, 125 s
- Mild case:
  - app1-app3 use 1200 B every 3 ms at 30 s, 50 s, and 65 s
  - app4 starts at 125 s with 1200 B every 10 ms
  - app5-app7 are delayed beyond the 180 s run and do not affect pre-failure congestion

Measurements
- Sender and receiver packet counts for all flows
- Receiver throughput, end-to-end delay, and received sequence progression vectors
- IPv4 no-route and interface-down drop counters
- Bottleneck queue vectors on r2.eth[1].queue:
  - queueLength
  - queueBitLength
  - queueingTime

Queue Assumption
- No custom queue discipline, AQM, or vendor-specific buffer model is configured.
- The bottleneck queue metrics come from the default INET interface queue attached to the bottleneck NIC in this simulator version.
- Interpret the queue telemetry as a simple simulator-default backlog approximation rather than as a calibrated device-buffer study.

Purpose
- Provide a controlled traffic-driven data-generation scenario where degradation emerges from rising demand and queue buildup on the primary path.
- Keep the setup deterministic, reproducible, and interpretable for later dataset generation.
